1
00:00:04,451 --> 00:00:14,066
The hindrances underlie the various difficulties we come across in meditation wandering mind, falling asleep, getting discouraged etc.

2
00:00:15,368 --> 00:00:19,995
We have to overcome the hindrances but not by fighting them to the death.

3
00:00:21,638 --> 00:00:23,000
How do we overcome our enemies?

4
00:00:23,920 --> 00:00:25,062
By making them our friends.

5
00:00:26,044 --> 00:00:31,792
I'm paraphrasing from Abraham Lincoln here but I think this applies wonderfully to our work with the hindrances.

6
00:00:32,954 --> 00:00:35,036
The analogy of a garden is also useful.

7
00:00:36,479 --> 00:00:40,906
A garden has grass and flowers and weeds and needs a gardener to tend it.

8
00:00:41,847 --> 00:00:49,761
So too our spiritual life has restful and uplifting aspects as well as hindrances and needs mindfulness to tend it.

9
00:00:50,942 --> 00:00:58,674
To a large extent the gardener can leave the grass and flowers alone, just watering or feeding them occasionally.

10
00:00:58,655 --> 00:01:07,500
The main work is in pulling up the weeds, if possible to do this while they are small and before they can flourish and spread their seeds.

11
00:01:09,150 --> 00:01:22,566
So too, a large part of vipassana involves working with the hindrances, if possible catching these early and letting mindfulness weed them out before they prompt us into thoughts or words or actions.

12
00:01:23,828 --> 00:01:29,634
It might not be as uplifting as watering the flowers of metta, but it can be satisfying in its own way.

13
00:01:32,337 --> 00:01:37,183
Now, as all you gardeners will know, the weeds have a way of coming back anyhow.

14
00:01:38,242 --> 00:01:48,489
Weeding has to be a long-term commitment and when we've done our share for the day to congratulate ourselves and feel the satisfaction of a job well done.

15
00:01:50,578 --> 00:02:03,893
Another gardening analogy that's useful here is to see that the basic constituents of the weed are the same as the flowers, roots and stalks and leaves, all made from carbon and hydrogen and oxygen.

16
00:02:04,733 --> 00:02:06,516
At heart there is no difference.

17
00:02:07,677 --> 00:02:14,223
And so the weed, once uprooted, can decompose to rich soil in which new flowers can grow.

18
00:02:16,246 --> 00:02:34,467
In the same way, the basic constituents of the hindrances are not in essence different to the more beautiful aspects of life, which also decompose into sensations and feelings and moods.

19
00:02:34,487 --> 00:02:39,974
What holds the weed together is a combination of greed, hatred and delusion.

20
00:02:40,629 --> 00:02:48,441
We uproot the weed by feeling these underlying drives within the sensations and emotions and thoughts.

21
00:02:49,924 --> 00:02:54,270
Once these drives are felt and recognized, they start to subside.

22
00:02:56,092 --> 00:02:58,036
That's one great power of mindfulness.

23
00:02:59,016 --> 00:03:01,760
It allows negativity to burn away.

24
00:03:04,306 --> 00:03:10,939
As the negativity in the hindrance burns away, its energy is transformed into the opposite virtue.

25
00:03:11,681 --> 00:03:17,933
Hatred to love, delusion to wisdom, greed to generosity, etc.

26
00:03:18,816 --> 00:03:20,460
So it's really worthwhile work.

27
00:03:22,323 --> 00:03:25,469
So what are these hindrances and how can we recognize them?

28
00:03:26,817 --> 00:03:45,006
The Buddha described them in five varieties Desire Aversion Dullness and Lethargy Restlessness and Doubt Starting with Desire This is the impulse of wanting that arises in response to pleasure.

29
00:03:46,348 --> 00:03:53,819
Although we might not feel particularly hungry when we see or smell pizza most of us would want to start nibbling a piece.

30
00:03:54,592 --> 00:04:02,371
We might be late for work, but when we step into the shower and feel the warm water flowing over us, we want to relax and enjoy it.

31
00:04:04,034 --> 00:04:07,563
Seeing an erotic image might stir sexual fantasies.

32
00:04:09,307 --> 00:04:13,276
A pleasant memory comes to mind and we want to start reminiscing.

33
00:04:15,247 --> 00:04:17,211
All advertising works on desire.

34
00:04:18,213 --> 00:04:26,908
We suddenly believe that we would be happy if only we had a BMW, hair coloured by L'Oreal, Starbucks coffee.

35
00:04:28,232 --> 00:04:37,728
When we get any pleasurable stimulus, physical or mental, we normally respond with desire, wanting to get more of the pleasure.

36
00:04:40,274 --> 00:04:51,369
Indulging some desires can obviously be harmful and lead to problems like overeating, drug addiction, sexual deviancy, power obsession and so on.

37
00:04:53,232 --> 00:04:55,754
On the other hand, many desires are beneficial.

38
00:04:57,557 --> 00:04:59,680
The desire for food keeps us alive.

39
00:05:00,641 --> 00:05:04,447
Reminiscing about a pleasant memory can help us generate goodwill.

40
00:05:06,250 --> 00:05:10,095
Desire for friends helps us to develop social skills.

41
00:05:11,711 --> 00:05:14,014
And desire drives our spiritual journey.

42
00:05:14,855 --> 00:05:19,819
The desire for enlightenment, for happiness, the wish to relieve suffering.

43
00:05:20,920 --> 00:05:22,982
These propel us along the path.

44
00:05:26,386 --> 00:05:28,848
So there's no need to judge our desires as wrong.

45
00:05:29,988 --> 00:05:32,031
Desire is neither right nor wrong.

46
00:05:33,091 --> 00:05:36,355
It simply arises in response to what we feel is pleasant.

47
00:05:37,375 --> 00:05:38,817
It's part of human nature.

48
00:05:40,567 --> 00:05:53,827
In daily life we need to be able to judge whether a desire is skilful like wanting to put on a hat when our head feels cold or unskilful like calling in sick when we want to watch Wimbledon.

49
00:05:56,091 --> 00:06:00,377
But in formal meditation practice we rarely have to go to the trouble of judging.

50
00:06:01,720 --> 00:06:03,403
This simplifies matters.

51
00:06:04,598 --> 00:06:23,401
All we have to do is to get to know what desire feels like, to learn to recognize this basic human urge for the good things in life, and to trust that mindfulness is digging away at the roots of desire as we simply feel its effects on our mind and body.

52
00:06:26,245 --> 00:06:28,747
Here again we have the magic of mindfulness.

53
00:06:29,668 --> 00:06:34,555
Very quietly, without fuss, it transforms whatever it meets.

54
00:06:38,821 --> 00:06:40,524
So what does desire feel like?

55
00:06:41,925 --> 00:06:46,754
Look out for a sense of pulling towards something or being pulled towards something.

56
00:06:48,377 --> 00:06:52,384
I often find I'm leaning forward slightly when desire is manifesting.

57
00:06:53,586 --> 00:07:02,922
For example, while you're waiting in the queue for food, are you totally relaxed or is there something like magnetism pulling you towards the sideboard?

58
00:07:07,339 --> 00:07:13,112
During sitting meditation we can sometimes feel that sense of pulling towards a pleasant experience.

59
00:07:14,956 --> 00:07:23,374
When I find myself slipping off into daydreams I counter this by taking an interest in this whole business of pleasure and desire.

60
00:07:24,797 --> 00:07:27,642
I feel the pleasure that the daydream is giving me.

61
00:07:28,670 --> 00:07:33,036
My mind is drawn towards the pleasant movie that the daydream is projecting.

62
00:07:34,057 --> 00:07:36,021
There may be a slight smile on my face.

63
00:07:37,043 --> 00:07:42,029
There is often a warm, billowy sensation around my chest or waist.

64
00:07:43,692 --> 00:07:46,716
There may be pleasant tingles running up and down my neck.

65
00:07:48,639 --> 00:07:53,326
As well as these pleasant sensations, I can feel a sense of strain.

66
00:07:54,252 --> 00:07:59,877
tension on my face perhaps, or a kind of desperate need to believe in the daydream.

67
00:08:01,798 --> 00:08:08,406
Nowadays I can easily recognize this straining and desperation as manifestations of desire.

68
00:08:08,446 --> 00:08:20,918
And I can feel the anxiety inherent in desire, the fear that all pleasure will be lost if I lose my grip on those gorgeous sensations.

69
00:08:23,850 --> 00:08:29,355
The wonderful thing is that our being, physical and mental, learns from experience.

70
00:08:31,177 --> 00:08:39,985
Feeling the desperation and tension associated with desire, I am nowadays more willing to relax my hold on the pleasure of the daydream.

71
00:08:41,407 --> 00:08:43,609
The desire to daydream fades away.

72
00:08:43,668 --> 00:08:51,816
As desire burns itself out, we grow more content.

73
00:08:52,758 --> 00:09:02,407
Those insatiable urges for more, more, more, which are so typical of our consumer society, lose some of their grip.

74
00:09:02,427 --> 00:09:07,272
We begin to trust that things are actually fine just as they are.

75
00:09:08,933 --> 00:09:12,157
What a relief!

76
00:09:12,177 --> 00:09:17,981
Now I made it sound easy, but in fact we will all be working with desire until we're fully enlightened.

77
00:09:19,043 --> 00:09:21,785
So letting go of deep desires is not easy.

78
00:09:23,268 --> 00:09:29,216
It can be quite scary, but this is an example of working with the hindrance of aversion.

79
00:09:31,181 --> 00:09:44,701
Aversion is at the root of fear, anger, hatred, and at a milder level we can feel aversion in irritation, impatience, sulkiness and other emotions.

80
00:09:47,111 --> 00:09:53,438
Aversion is actually another form of desire, the wish to get rid of what we don't like.

81
00:09:55,100 --> 00:09:58,783
We normally respond with aversion to any unpleasant stimulus.

82
00:10:00,265 --> 00:10:04,450
Our knee starts throbbing and we want to move or stretch to relieve the pain.

83
00:10:05,671 --> 00:10:10,275
Someone coughs, disturbing our peaceful meditation and we want to murder them.

84
00:10:12,357 --> 00:10:14,841
Many of our emotions spring from aversion.

85
00:10:16,711 --> 00:10:20,275
We get bad news and react with anger and anxiety.

86
00:10:20,316 --> 00:10:25,822
Our partner leaves us for another person and we are overcome with jealousy.

87
00:10:28,105 --> 00:10:31,610
We fail a test and are devastated by despair.

88
00:10:36,957 --> 00:10:42,465
The Buddha described our aversive reaction as getting shot by two arrows.

89
00:10:43,929 --> 00:10:50,039
The first arrow is the unpleasant sensation, the knee pain or the disturbing cough.

90
00:10:51,341 --> 00:10:54,508
The second arrow is our aversive reaction.

91
00:10:55,769 --> 00:11:03,643
Unwittingly we stab ourselves in reaction to the first arrow and it's the second arrow which really hurts.

92
00:11:06,644 --> 00:11:14,339
Aversion can have a very negative impact on our lives, but in some cases the aversive reaction is the wise one.

93
00:11:16,123 --> 00:11:21,312
If we witness cruelty, anger may spur us to do something to stop this.

94
00:11:23,177 --> 00:11:27,605
Feeling shame after being caught cheating persuades us not to cheat again.

95
00:11:28,462 --> 00:11:40,677
So we need to make friends with the experience of aversion, so that we are not afraid of our anger when anger is the wise response, willing to feel shame when shame is the wise response.

96
00:11:42,599 --> 00:11:51,349
Aversion is very much linked with wisdom, so working with aversion strengthens our ability to live wisely.

97
00:11:54,028 --> 00:12:05,143
So again, it's important not to judge aversion when it arises in our meditation, but to let our system learn to recognize it, make friends with it.

98
00:12:08,506 --> 00:12:10,208
How can we recognize aversion?

99
00:12:14,594 --> 00:12:18,619
Physical pain is one we all have to work with from time to time.

100
00:12:19,982 --> 00:12:22,446
See if you can locate the basic pain.

101
00:12:23,527 --> 00:12:25,528
The throbbing in the knee, for example.

102
00:12:27,572 --> 00:12:32,037
And then let yourself feel how the rest of the body is sitting with that.

103
00:12:34,119 --> 00:12:35,441
Is your face in a grimace?

104
00:12:36,522 --> 00:12:37,943
Are your shoulders hunched?

105
00:12:38,804 --> 00:12:40,365
Is your stomach in a knot?

106
00:12:41,847 --> 00:12:43,509
Is your thigh tense?

107
00:12:45,514 --> 00:12:52,770
You may also get an overall sense of pushing, as if your body is physically trying to push the pain away.

108
00:12:54,716 --> 00:13:04,317
Or it can manifest as a sense of the body straining to get away from the pain, as if it's trying to tear itself away from the painful site.

109
00:13:08,616 --> 00:13:17,725
While physical pain is a great teacher, we shouldn't let our enthusiasm for enlightenment run away with our common sense about how to take care of ourselves.

110
00:13:19,586 --> 00:13:24,072
So when the pain gets too bad, it's best to move so as to relieve it.

111
00:13:25,633 --> 00:13:35,282
But move mindfully, as this part of the meditation can also be a great teacher, especially if you move very slowly.

112
00:13:36,899 --> 00:13:42,289
Keeping your attention in the body as it moves, you might feel the pain fading away.

113
00:13:42,350 --> 00:13:51,129
Also, out of the corner of your eyes, so to speak, you might notice your mood brightening.

114
00:13:51,149 --> 00:13:55,818
This is an example of aversion fading away.

115
00:13:58,279 --> 00:14:08,589
It's a really powerful experience because it shows us that the real suffering in the situation was in our mental reaction rather than in our knee.

116
00:14:10,490 --> 00:14:18,857
The anxiety or bad humour provoked by the pain was the real source of misery, not the physical sensations in your knee.

117
00:14:23,883 --> 00:14:26,565
I remember one time when I injured my back.

118
00:14:27,996 --> 00:14:39,851
I was acutely aware of the injury and walking very carefully and stiffly to avoid any sudden pulls and lying down for hours each evening after work.

119
00:14:41,333 --> 00:14:46,860
I felt imprisoned by the pain, unable to relax or enjoy anything because of it.

120
00:14:49,023 --> 00:14:54,509
But because I was being mindful, I realised that I couldn't actually feel the pain.

121
00:14:56,092 --> 00:15:03,583
When I put my attention on the middle of my back where I knew I had the pain, all I felt was a blank.

122
00:15:05,225 --> 00:15:12,857
This is one effect of aversion, causing so much mental disturbance that the basic sensation itself is suppressed.

123
00:15:14,799 --> 00:15:20,008
It was a few days before my mind calmed down enough to be able to feel the pain.

124
00:15:21,236 --> 00:15:24,179
and ironically I no longer felt imprisoned by it.

125
00:15:24,860 --> 00:15:26,163
I could enjoy life again.

126
00:15:28,605 --> 00:15:39,518
This really helped me believe that the problem with pain doesn't stem from the physical sensation but from the mental reaction of aversion.

127
00:15:44,724 --> 00:15:49,809
Another way to see this is to alternate your focus for attention.

128
00:15:51,341 --> 00:15:56,148
If your right knee is throbbing, let your attention dwell there for a while.

129
00:15:57,590 --> 00:16:00,533
Then let your attention shift to your left knee.

130
00:16:02,355 --> 00:16:07,061
As you switch, you might just feel a slight lightening of your mood.

131
00:16:08,763 --> 00:16:16,572
If so, you may also realise that it's the mood that is determining your sense of suffering, not the pain itself.

132
00:16:21,498 --> 00:16:26,605
Now it can be very difficult to sit with pain and let yourself feel all this.

133
00:16:27,787 --> 00:16:37,782
Your mind may be buzzing with thoughts of the sort, this is mad, I'm going to injure myself or why am I torturing myself like this and so on.

134
00:16:39,384 --> 00:16:43,109
So let's remind ourselves why we try to sit and bear the pain.

135
00:16:45,111 --> 00:16:49,057
It's to let our system learn about the second arrow.

136
00:16:50,505 --> 00:17:02,144
The more clearly we see that the hurt results from our reaction, our wish to get rid of pain, the more willing we are to stop stabbing ourselves with the second arrow.

137
00:17:03,365 --> 00:17:11,618
Gradually we learn to relax around the pain and may even experience moments of compassion for a being in pain.

138
00:17:13,401 --> 00:17:18,910
The weeds of aversion are transforming into the flower of compassion.

139
00:17:24,037 --> 00:17:28,224
we can work mindfully with difficult emotions in a similar way.

140
00:17:32,152 --> 00:17:35,938
Suppose we start feeling irritated and angry, for example.

141
00:17:37,981 --> 00:17:46,837
If we don't recognize this as a form of aversion, we could spend the whole meditation period mulling over angry thoughts.

142
00:17:47,407 --> 00:17:53,095
Or we could judge the meditation as useless, thinking we can't meditate when we're angry.

143
00:17:54,237 --> 00:17:57,161
In both cases, aversion is flourishing.

144
00:17:58,623 --> 00:18:02,207
The weed has been allowed to grow and spread its seeds.

145
00:18:05,030 --> 00:18:12,240
But if we recognize that the weed of anger is springing up, we can start digging away at it mindfully.

146
00:18:14,463 --> 00:18:16,385
How is anger experienced?

147
00:18:17,580 --> 00:18:25,112
The angry thoughts, instead of believing them and following them up, can you note them as thinking?

148
00:18:25,894 --> 00:18:26,334
Thinking.

149
00:18:29,398 --> 00:18:30,601
Are your lips pursed?

150
00:18:32,963 --> 00:18:34,406
Is your jaw clenched?

151
00:18:36,430 --> 00:18:37,692
How does your stomach feel?

152
00:18:40,055 --> 00:18:43,200
This approach digs around the root of the anger.

153
00:18:45,256 --> 00:18:51,184
It helps us acknowledge anger as just another manifestation of this body-mind system we inhabit.

154
00:18:53,307 --> 00:18:59,917
We begin to relax with the emotion, not to be so judgmental about it or let it rule our lives.

155
00:19:01,420 --> 00:19:08,631
Again, we may sometimes feel compassion for a being going through the pain of anger.

156
00:19:13,201 --> 00:19:18,930
One other aspect of aversion that troubles most of us is our habit of judging.

157
00:19:18,970 --> 00:19:25,661
I've been saying there's no need to judge desire or aversion as wrong.

158
00:19:25,681 --> 00:19:29,326
I remind myself regularly of this too.

159
00:19:31,770 --> 00:19:38,382
But the habit of judging goes so deep that I don't always remember my own advice when I'm out of my comfort zone.

160
00:19:40,048 --> 00:19:45,560
And then, of course, we can start judging ourselves because we're judging and the misery deepens.

161
00:19:48,808 --> 00:19:58,210
It's wonderful to be able to note judging, judging, and get to know the fierce judginess that demands and expects only the best.

162
00:20:01,700 --> 00:20:10,669
In mindful awareness, the judge will also boil down to sensations and feelings and thoughts, nothing to be so scared of.

163
00:20:14,733 --> 00:20:16,776
How does the judge manifest in you?

164
00:20:18,998 --> 00:20:26,526
In me, the judge makes me feel top-heavy with the weight of disapproval I feel in my forehead especially.

165
00:20:30,134 --> 00:20:35,804
At times then I can also feel the scared child cowering in my chest and throat.

166
00:20:38,909 --> 00:20:45,098
Nowadays the scared child and judge often find a way to compromise and forgive each other.

167
00:20:47,542 --> 00:20:56,157
The judge asks forgiveness for harshness, the child for mistrusting the protection and guidance being offered by the judge.

168
00:21:01,656 --> 00:21:09,909
One confusing aspect of working with aversion is that the unpleasant feelings are amplified in mindful awareness.

169
00:21:13,053 --> 00:21:18,441
We avoid or suppress those painful feelings when we're letting the aversion flourish.

170
00:21:20,022 --> 00:21:24,609
Mulling over angry thoughts, dismissing the situation is a waste of time.

171
00:21:27,053 --> 00:21:33,661
When we dig mindfully at the roots of aversion, we begin to feel the pain of what we've been trying to avoid.

172
00:21:36,644 --> 00:21:37,925
This can be confusing.

173
00:21:39,428 --> 00:21:43,673
We thought mindfulness was supposed to relieve suffering, not make it worse.

174
00:21:46,175 --> 00:21:49,180
So this hindrance can be quite a challenge to work with.

175
00:21:51,116 --> 00:21:52,318
But there's no way out.

176
00:21:53,240 --> 00:22:00,769
It's only by experiencing the pain of aversion that our system learns to recognize that it is hurting itself.

177
00:22:03,372 --> 00:22:09,180
Each demonstration of this painful truth strengthens our faith in the process.

178
00:22:14,625 --> 00:22:17,529
Working with desire, we learn to let go.

179
00:22:18,471 --> 00:22:21,696
Working with aversion we learn to come forth.

180
00:22:23,961 --> 00:22:37,122
Often it's like walking a tightrope as we step gingerly from one to the other, relaxing the tense grip of desire, bringing attention towards what we fear or dislike.

181
00:22:40,627 --> 00:22:48,364
Along with delusion, desire and aversion are the basic urges holding the other hindrances together.

182
00:22:50,048 --> 00:22:56,882
In fact, working with any of the hindrances is strengthening our ability to work with all of them.

183
00:23:01,537 --> 00:23:10,886
So let's look at a third hindrance, dullness and lethargy, or sloth and torpor, if you prefer the formal translation.

184
00:23:12,910 --> 00:23:26,125
This is a familiar one for most of us, snoozing happily through the hour's meditation, occasionally jerking awake to realize we're in the meditation hall and hoping we're not snoring before nodding off again.

185
00:23:27,967 --> 00:23:30,108
It's such an alluring hindrance.

186
00:23:30,663 --> 00:23:35,088
We feel so happy and relaxed as we slip off into unconsciousness.

187
00:23:36,971 --> 00:23:43,480
Sometimes we don't actually fall asleep, but the mind becomes heavy, sluggish and dull.

188
00:23:45,963 --> 00:23:51,570
Remember, all we have to do is register the thoughts, feelings and sensations involved.

189
00:23:53,113 --> 00:23:55,876
But how can we register anything if we're falling asleep?

190
00:23:58,034 --> 00:24:15,557
That's our work, to stay conscious enough to feel the strong pull towards sleep, noting sleepy, sleepy, and to find the energy to note dullness, dullness, when that heavy blanket covers our mind.

191
00:24:18,941 --> 00:24:25,829
An upright posture helps us to keep awake, so straighten the spine at the first sense of sleepiness.

192
00:24:27,025 --> 00:24:29,186
Noting itself is energizing.

193
00:24:30,367 --> 00:24:34,772
So see if you can put more energy into noting sleepy, sleepy.

194
00:24:36,994 --> 00:24:41,960
Try to stir up interest by asking yourself whether this is a pleasant experience.

195
00:24:42,839 --> 00:24:44,362
Are you enjoying being sleepy?

196
00:24:45,482 --> 00:24:47,964
Often there's a lovely sense of being safe.

197
00:24:49,066 --> 00:24:51,568
Why not try to stay awake enough to enjoy this?

198
00:24:53,750 --> 00:24:56,913
Also, there may be nice tingly sensations somewhere.

199
00:24:58,227 --> 00:25:02,053
Or do you feel heavy, leaden, aversive to the experience?

200
00:25:03,394 --> 00:25:06,440
Try to dredge up the energy to note all these.

201
00:25:09,003 --> 00:25:16,717
If that doesn't work and you keep dropping off, then try opening your eyes and look at anything bright.

202
00:25:17,818 --> 00:25:19,500
The sky outside, for example.

203
00:25:21,084 --> 00:25:23,728
Big wide staring eyes are best.

204
00:25:26,222 --> 00:25:31,769
Joseph Goldstein says he imagines there are toothpicks between his eyelids propping them open.

205
00:25:34,011 --> 00:25:41,180
And if that doesn't work, try elevating your hands a few inches so they need some energy to keep them elevated.

206
00:25:42,902 --> 00:25:47,267
You can also use whatever mental stimuli might work to keep you awake.

207
00:25:48,567 --> 00:25:52,752
Reciting a poem you know by heart or the Metta Sutta if you know that.

208
00:25:54,151 --> 00:26:00,240
And if all that doesn't work, then stand up.

209
00:26:00,259 --> 00:26:12,958
Again, remember that you're not trying to get rid of sleepiness or dullness, but only to stay awake enough to feel their manifestation as sensations, feelings, thoughts.

210
00:26:14,881 --> 00:26:23,854
As we do this, our system becomes more able to deal with powerful forces of suppression that keep us dull and passive in life.

211
00:26:27,461 --> 00:26:37,419
At one retreat, I was working a lot with dullness and sleepiness, until I suddenly recognised the sense of waiting running through them.

212
00:26:38,961 --> 00:26:46,054
I realised I was waiting for the dullness to pass, not wanting to engage with the experience.

213
00:26:47,998 --> 00:26:50,382
With that, the dullness disappeared.

214
00:26:52,183 --> 00:27:08,249
But afterwards, when I went to meetings at work where I didn't have much to contribute, I often noticed that subtle undercurrent of waiting for this to be over as a form of passivity which was preventing me from engaging with the meeting.

215
00:27:11,053 --> 00:27:16,020
Whenever I recognised this, to my surprise, I would suddenly pipe up and say something.

216
00:27:17,583 --> 00:27:20,587
And it was always a useful contribution and well received.

217
00:27:21,984 --> 00:27:30,221
So the work on retreat with sleepiness helps me become brighter, more forthright and more engaged with others in daily life.

218
00:27:35,351 --> 00:27:41,563
So don't judge a sleepy meditation as a useless one, an easy mistake to make.

219
00:27:43,416 --> 00:27:53,151
If you're doing your best to stay awake despite the powerfully suppressive urges towards sleep then you are uprooting weeds at a great rate.

220
00:27:53,211 --> 00:28:07,593
The fourth hindrance is restlessness which the Buddha links with remorse, guilt and shame.

221
00:28:10,156 --> 00:28:12,359
We can become physically restless

222
00:28:13,031 --> 00:28:19,799
fidgeting, scratching our head, looking at our watch, and repeatedly adjusting our posture.

223
00:28:21,961 --> 00:28:29,069
Or it can manifest as a mental state, as our mind hops from one inconsequential thought to another.

224
00:28:31,532 --> 00:28:41,824
We might not be aware of the underlying emotions of guilt, shame and remorse, but these can manifest as a knot of worry or self-judgment.

225
00:28:43,980 --> 00:28:47,166
It's so easy to believe our worries and judgments.

226
00:28:49,250 --> 00:28:59,347
If we do, we can spend the whole meditation period in a frenzy of thought, probably not even noticing that we're shifting around and fidgeting as well.

227
00:29:00,769 --> 00:29:05,077
This is letting the weed of restlessness flourish and sow its seeds.

228
00:29:06,931 --> 00:29:17,801
So our first task is to recognize, oh, this is restlessness, or this is worrying, this is judging.

229
00:29:21,612 --> 00:29:32,585
If we can do that, the gardener of mindfulness starts the great work of weeding, replacing each persuasive worry with the note worrying, worrying.

230
00:29:33,727 --> 00:29:36,730
We begin to feel the manifestation of this hindrance.

231
00:29:38,653 --> 00:29:42,877
If you find yourself shifting around on the cushion, feel the movement.

232
00:29:44,700 --> 00:29:47,222
If you want to scratch your head, desist.

233
00:29:48,263 --> 00:29:50,386
Feel the itchy sensation instead.

234
00:29:52,730 --> 00:29:56,512
I often get sudden prickles like needles sticking into my thighs.

235
00:29:56,993 --> 00:29:58,295
They really make me jump.

236
00:30:00,457 --> 00:30:04,759
Sometimes the restlessness fades away after a while of mindful awareness.

237
00:30:06,281 --> 00:30:12,086
Sometimes we can't maintain mindfulness and get caught up repeatedly into worrying and fidgeting.

238
00:30:13,768 --> 00:30:21,775
It can help to open your eyes and gaze at something in the room to ground you as the worries swirl around in your mind.

239
00:30:23,594 --> 00:30:31,662
As some of you will know I underwent major surgery in 2013 and lost my voice box.

240
00:30:31,682 --> 00:30:35,385
For weeks following this I was seething with restlessness and worry.

241
00:30:36,807 --> 00:30:43,113
The first days in ICU were the worst but then I was put in a ward and luckily I was beside a window.

242
00:30:43,133 --> 00:30:50,259
There was a tree outside and as soon as I saw it my eyes became glued to the tree.

243
00:30:51,556 --> 00:30:57,844
I even sent my visitor Margaret away, though I had relied on her so much while I was in ICU.

244
00:30:59,346 --> 00:31:02,711
The tree was what my psyche wanted, not human company.

245
00:31:04,593 --> 00:31:14,846
Although I still had a cauldron of restlessness and worry bubbling away inside, it was as if the worries could die away into the strong, steady branches of the tree.

246
00:31:18,438 --> 00:31:36,747
Remember that all we're trying to do is to let the hindrance manifest in whatever way it wants to, using whatever supports we can find so as to maintain mindfulness rather than believe the worrying or judging thoughts or succumb to the urge to fidget.

247
00:31:38,990 --> 00:31:43,196
All the while restlessness is expending its energy.

248
00:31:45,656 --> 00:31:55,325
The weeds are springing up at a great rate maybe an alarming rate but each one meets with mindfulness before it gets a chance to sow its seeds.

249
00:31:57,547 --> 00:32:07,036
In my own case I can look back and see that a huge level of restlessness burned its energy away during those first weeks post-op.

250
00:32:10,018 --> 00:32:15,343
As it did I began to sense a vast ocean of calm that permeates the world

251
00:32:17,432 --> 00:32:32,698
In my imagination, it's there in the spaces between things, quiet and gentle, willing to let my flurries and worries sink into it, endlessly receptive to all my woes.

252
00:32:36,983 --> 00:32:42,292
So I have great trust now in the benefit of sitting still with this hindrance.

253
00:32:43,251 --> 00:32:48,118
opening my eyes to look at something if I need to anchor my mind more firmly.

254
00:32:48,140 --> 00:33:02,761
I might feel almost as if I'm exploding, but after a while I often sense again that quiet ocean lapping at the borders of restlessness.

255
00:33:05,559 --> 00:33:13,329
The explosion of sensations and feelings shoot into its darkness and disappear, leaving no trace.

256
00:33:21,180 --> 00:33:23,403
The final hindrance is doubt.

257
00:33:26,146 --> 00:33:34,538
It's really challenging for us to sit with our desires and aversions, nodding off to sleep only to awaken all fidgety and worried.

258
00:33:35,632 --> 00:33:40,097
So who could blame us for doubting whether any of this is doing us any good?

259
00:33:42,221 --> 00:33:49,330
We come on retreat with high hopes of deep insight but after a day or two we can get dispirited.

260
00:33:51,034 --> 00:33:54,798
In our disappointment we fall into the hindrance of doubt.

261
00:33:57,383 --> 00:34:04,692
Sometimes we doubt the teachings and wonder whether we should go back to Christianity or try some other path.

262
00:34:06,664 --> 00:34:08,248
Sometimes we doubt the teacher.

263
00:34:08,307 --> 00:34:11,894
They don't seem inspiring or to have much wisdom.

264
00:34:13,878 --> 00:34:15,722
At other times we doubt ourselves.

265
00:34:16,925 --> 00:34:21,634
We think we're not up to this practice.

266
00:34:21,653 --> 00:34:27,846
Just like worry, it's so, so easy to believe the thoughts generated by doubt.

267
00:34:29,632 --> 00:34:36,282
If we do, we can spend the whole meditation period mulling over unanswerable questions.

268
00:34:37,425 --> 00:34:38,606
Is this the right way?

269
00:34:38,666 --> 00:34:41,192
Does she know what she's talking about?

270
00:34:41,251 --> 00:34:45,498
Even more harmfully, we can confirm our doubts.

271
00:34:46,940 --> 00:34:47,902
I'm useless at this.

272
00:34:47,963 --> 00:34:49,385
I can't meditate.

273
00:34:50,286 --> 00:34:52,550
I should have known better than to come here.

274
00:34:56,934 --> 00:34:59,878
Doubt can have a very negative impact on our lives.

275
00:35:00,699 --> 00:35:01,940
It makes for cynicism.

276
00:35:02,501 --> 00:35:05,365
We see the flaw in everything and everybody.

277
00:35:06,327 --> 00:35:08,630
We grow suspicious and mistrustful.

278
00:35:10,791 --> 00:35:16,059
One reason we indulge doubtful thoughts is that they're easy on our psyche.

279
00:35:19,103 --> 00:35:20,123
They don't challenge us.

280
00:35:22,626 --> 00:35:24,849
They look to pass doubts and confirm them.

281
00:35:25,807 --> 00:35:26,748
I can't do this.

282
00:35:27,309 --> 00:35:28,590
I knew I wouldn't be able to.

283
00:35:30,612 --> 00:35:34,936
In the short term, it actually feels comforting to confirm our doubts.

284
00:35:36,297 --> 00:35:38,440
We can feel strong because we were right.

285
00:35:39,061 --> 00:35:40,181
We're always right.

286
00:35:41,844 --> 00:35:46,989
Doubt forms an effective border to prevent change and the pain of growth.

287
00:35:50,271 --> 00:35:54,836
But as with all the hindrances, doubt can be appropriate at times.

288
00:35:56,099 --> 00:36:03,827
If someone lets us down repeatedly, it makes sense to doubt their word and take steps to protect ourselves against further hurt.

289
00:36:05,509 --> 00:36:14,318
On the spiritual path, we are continually being pushed beyond our comfort zone, needing to verify the teachings again and again.

290
00:36:14,358 --> 00:36:16,621
These are healthy doubts.

291
00:36:18,041 --> 00:36:24,469
We need to be able to note doubting, doubting and be with ease with that state.

292
00:36:28,128 --> 00:36:32,594
The big step is to become aware that this is nothing more than the hindrance of doubt.

293
00:36:33,855 --> 00:36:44,509
Sounds easy, but those thoughts can be very, very persuasive, deliciously confirming of our sense of knowing exactly what to expect of ourselves and the world.

294
00:36:47,032 --> 00:36:53,780
If you get as far as noting that you are being hijacked by a storm of doubt, that is a major achievement.

295
00:36:55,465 --> 00:37:04,398
From then on, it's a question of maintaining that perspective rather than falling into the temptation to believe the thoughts generated by doubt.

296
00:37:06,039 --> 00:37:16,175
Ground yourself in your body, feeling your posture or the breath to provide a solid foundation for your observation of this hindrance.

297
00:37:16,195 --> 00:37:21,742
Keep noting, doubting, doubting so that the thoughts won't get a foothold.

298
00:37:24,827 --> 00:37:28,413
But remember that we're not trying to overcome doubt by suppressing it.

299
00:37:29,554 --> 00:37:35,804
We're letting it manifest, getting to know the experience, allowing ourselves to feel doubtful.

300
00:37:37,746 --> 00:37:40,811
Sometimes I tend to space out when some doubt arises.

301
00:37:42,253 --> 00:37:49,063
Physical sensations become vague and distant, as if I'm in a cloud where things seem intangible.

302
00:37:50,815 --> 00:37:55,280
I have a sense that something is wrong but can't put my finger on what it is.

303
00:37:56,681 --> 00:38:03,990
The noting word unsure, unsure is helpful here or distant, distant.

304
00:38:05,813 --> 00:38:12,742
Then I might become aware of some quiet but insistent thoughts that repeat themselves over and over.

305
00:38:13,862 --> 00:38:17,126
No, no, no, for example.

306
00:38:18,742 --> 00:38:26,760
I change the noting word to insisting, insisting, to help me feel the intensity associated with the thought.

307
00:38:28,523 --> 00:38:33,072
This has a physical component, tension in my face perhaps.

308
00:38:34,184 --> 00:38:39,530
Once I can find the physical manifestation, it's much easier to maintain mindfulness.

309
00:38:40,771 --> 00:38:52,884
The thoughts might subside while the tension grows until eventually I feel myself capitulate and another thought, maybe, maybe, slowly starts to manifest.

310
00:38:54,425 --> 00:39:02,554
Thus, some boundary to my psyche is beginning to dissolve and self-doubt edges towards self-confidence.

311
00:39:06,246 --> 00:39:09,393
Self-doubt can also manifest as anxiety.

312
00:39:09,434 --> 00:39:15,927
The doubtful thoughts are formed as questions like, am I doing this right?

313
00:39:15,967 --> 00:39:26,230
I find this easier to work with because in my experience anyhow, anxiety is more tangible and has more physical energy.

314
00:39:27,222 --> 00:39:39,003
Again, it's a question of allowing the stresses and strains of anxiety to be felt, various tensions in the body perhaps, and the breath may grow shallow and rapid.

315
00:39:40,905 --> 00:39:49,601
I usually find some pleasant tingly sensations as well, and can feel how the anxious thoughts seem to buzz around those.

316
00:39:52,264 --> 00:39:57,030
The driving force of anxiety, in my experience, is quite a pleasant buzz.

317
00:39:58,210 --> 00:40:02,635
But there is a lot of unpleasant physical tension needed to support the buzz.

318
00:40:03,715 --> 00:40:10,902
And as my attention broadens to take this in, the buzz of anxiety loses its pleasure and starts to subside.

319
00:40:14,847 --> 00:40:19,891
Self-doubt was the last temptation to trouble the Buddha before his enlightenment.

320
00:40:21,559 --> 00:40:31,275
To overcome it, he touched the ground with his fingers, calling the earth as witness that he had done enough work to merit enlightenment.

321
00:40:34,719 --> 00:40:39,768
One teacher suggested we follow his example when we are assailed by doubts.

322
00:40:40,889 --> 00:40:45,356
I found it very helpful at times, and so I'm passing on this suggestion.

323
00:40:48,626 --> 00:40:53,918
In summary then, the hindrances represent our various challenges in meditation.

324
00:40:55,420 --> 00:40:57,666
They come in five different flavours.

325
00:40:58,969 --> 00:41:09,471
Desire to keep hold of the lovely stuff, aversion to the rotten stuff, falling asleep, getting restless and being assailed by doubt.

326
00:41:11,289 --> 00:41:16,735
Now you don't have to worry about being able to categorise each difficulty as one or other of these.

327
00:41:17,697 --> 00:41:23,023
In fact, several hindrances can be working together at times to make our lives miserable.

328
00:41:24,864 --> 00:41:29,409
For example, anger includes a pleasant buzz of self-righteousness.

329
00:41:29,750 --> 00:41:33,634
Impatience includes a pleasant suggestion of self-importance.

330
00:41:36,936 --> 00:41:39,340
Sometimes we get a multiple hindrance attack.

331
00:41:40,855 --> 00:41:45,159
Our mind wanders restlessly, picking up one thought then another.

332
00:41:46,280 --> 00:41:48,101
We get angry at being so restless.

333
00:41:49,182 --> 00:41:57,050
We want to get in control of the restless, angry mind to make it conform to what we think a good meditator's mind should be.

334
00:41:58,210 --> 00:42:02,855
But we can't get on top of things and start to doubt our ability to meditate.

335
00:42:03,956 --> 00:42:08,500
In despair, we grow sulky, we dull out and fall asleep.

336
00:42:10,757 --> 00:42:17,264
At other times we find we can relax and feel each passing disturbance without reacting.

337
00:42:18,867 --> 00:42:21,989
We feel the prickles of restlessness but let them be.

338
00:42:22,030 --> 00:42:26,355
To our surprise perhaps restlessness dies away.

339
00:42:27,215 --> 00:42:36,867
After a moment's quiet the tension of anxiety surfaces and we let it fill our bodies and minds as much as it wishes till it too subsides.

340
00:42:38,652 --> 00:42:48,284
We can let each hindrance grow until we recognize it from its basic manifestation as physical sensations, moods and thoughts.

341
00:42:50,387 --> 00:42:59,539
Upon recognition, the hindrance dies away to leave a moment's peace till we feel the next one sprouting up, disturbing us.

342
00:43:00,579 --> 00:43:01,340
That's okay.

343
00:43:02,461 --> 00:43:03,583
This is our path.

344
00:43:04,764 --> 00:43:06,987
The hindrances form its borders.

345
00:43:09,313 --> 00:43:13,552
May we and all beings be free from suffering.

